04599nam a22008055i 9780271031903DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20152004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710319037 a10.1515/97802710319032doi  a(DE-B1597)583689  a(OCoLC)1266228897  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320/.09731 aGunnell, John G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagining the American Polity :bPolitical Science and the Discourse of Democracy /cJohn G. Gunnell. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2015] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tONE The Democratic Concept -- tTWO The State of Democracy -- tTHREE The Discovery of American Pluralism -- tFOUR The Theory of Democratic Pluralism -- tFIVE From Pluralism to Liberalism -- tSIX Pluralism Redux -- tAppendix: Telling the Story of Political Science -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmericans have long prided themselves on living in a country that serves as a beacon of democracy to the world, but from the time of the founding they have also engaged in debates over what the criteria for democracy are as they seek to validate their faith in the United States as a democratic regime. In this book John Gunnell shows how the academic discipline of political science has contributed in a major way to this ongoing dialogue, thereby playing a significant role in political education and the formulation of popular conceptions of American democracy. Using the distinctive “internalist” approach he has developed for writing intellectual history, Gunnell traces the dynamics of conceptual change and continuity as American political science evolved from a focus in the nineteenth century on the idea of the state, through the emergence of a pluralist theory of democracy in the 1920s and its transfiguration into liberalism in the mid-1930s, up to the rearticulation of pluralist theory in the 1950s and its resurgence, yet again, in the 1990s. Along the way he explores how political scientists have grappled with a fundamental question about popular sovereignty: Does democracy require a people and a national democratic community, or can the requisites of democracy be achieved through fortuitous social configurations coupled with the design of certain institutional mechanisms?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aDemocracyxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aDemocracyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical sciencexHistoryxUnited States. 0aPolitical sciencezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmerican Politics.  aHistory.  aJohn G. Gunnell.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitical Theory.  ademocracy.  ademocratic theory.  ainternalist.  aunited states.  aus.  ausa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271031903?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271031903423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271031903/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK